message.content:
To be produced by the grammar the string must start from one of the two start-rules  

  S → NT33 NT12 or S → NT28 NT7.

1.  S → NT33 NT12 is impossible because the first token of every sentence generated by NT33 is either
    • the terminal ‘t67’, or  
    • the first token of NT11 (since NT33 → NT11 NT3 and NT11 → NT24 NT21).
    NT11 can only start with ‘t41’, ‘t2’, ‘t34’ or ‘t14’.  
    The given string begins with ‘t75’, so this branch is ruled out.

2.  Therefore the only possible start is S → NT28 NT7, with the first token produced by the
    terminal alternative NT28 → ‘t75’.  
    That leaves the remaining 21 tokens to be generated by NT7.

3.  NT7 can generate a sequence longer than one token only via  

        NT7 → NT13 NT26

    (its other options are the single terminals ‘t18’ and ‘t56’).  
    Hence the 21-token suffix must be split into a prefix produced by NT13 and a
    suffix produced by NT26.

4.  NT26 can begin with
        • the single terminal ‘t2’, or  
        • NT8 NT17, whose first token must be either ‘t34’ or ‘t14’ (because NT8 → ‘t34’ | ‘t14’ | …).

    The given suffix contains exactly one such candidate, the ‘t34’
    that appears as the 11-th token of the whole string.  
    Consequently

        tokens 2–10  (t50 t6 t19 t37 t18 t41 t56 t52 t4)  ← NT13  
        tokens 11–22 (t34 … t71)                         ← NT26.

5.  NT13 has only two binary forms:

        NT13 → NT20 NT4
        NT13 → NT24 NT16.

    • In NT13 → NT24 NT16, NT16 is a single terminal (‘t36’, ‘t37’ or ‘t81’).  
      The only possible placement for such a token in positions 2–10 is the
      ‘t37’ at position 5, so NT16 must be that ‘t37’ and NT24 would have to
      produce t50 t6 t19.  
      NT24, however, can only be the single terminal ‘t41’ or NT26 NT12,
      and neither of those possibilities can begin with ‘t50’.  
      Hence this rule cannot generate the required prefix.

    • In NT13 → NT20 NT4, NT20 must deliver the initial ‘t50’.
      Once NT20 chooses its terminal alternative ‘t50’, it contains no further
      symbols, so the eight remaining tokens (t6 … t4) would have to come from NT4.
      NT4, in turn, is either the single terminal ‘t16’ (contradicted by the
      required ‘t6’) or NT7 NT27.  
      A detailed case analysis of all ways NT7 NT27 might yield
      t6 t19 t37 t18 t41 t56 t52 t4 shows that NT27 can never produce a
      sequence whose first token is ‘t52’ and whose last token is ‘t4’,
      while NT7 can never start with ‘t6’.  
      Therefore this rule, too, cannot generate the nine-token prefix.

    Since neither alternative for NT13 works, NT13 cannot derive tokens 2–10.

6.  Because the only viable split of the 21-token suffix fails, NT7 cannot
    generate the remainder of the string, and so S → NT28 NT7 is impossible as well.

Hence no derivation from the start symbol S can yield the given 22-token string.

No

The grammar provides only two possibilities for expanding the start symbol:

1. S → NT33 NT12  
2. S → NT28 NT7  

Hence the last word of any sentence generated by the grammar must come from the second non-terminal on the right-hand side of one of these two rules.

Case 1: S → NT28 NT7  
• NT7 can derive   
  – the single lexical tokens t18 or t56, or  
  – a string whose final token is t2 (via NT7 → NT13 NT26, NT26 → t2).  
• Our string ends with t67, which is none of t18, t56, or t2.  
Therefore the string cannot arise from S → NT28 NT7.

Case 2: S → NT33 NT12  
• NT12 can derive  
  a) the single lexical token t16, or  
  b) NT33 NT17, where NT17 ultimately produces one of the tokens  
   t69, t31, t36, t37, t81 (NT17 has no ε-derivation).  
• In either sub-case, the last token produced by NT12 must be one of  
  t16, t69, t31, t36, t37, t81.  
• Again, our string ends with t67, which is not in that list.  

Since neither of the only two possible derivations for S can yield a sentence whose final token is t67, the given 24-token string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No
